13. Regia SoliS‚ etc.: quoted, as a specimen, from Ovid’s account of how Phaethon went to the palace of the sun-god, his father, and essayed to drive his chariot (Metam. II. 1-2).— Aureus axis, etc.: ibid. II. 107—108.

14. Sine me, etc.: These first seven lines, which are trans- lated, very likely by Seneca himself, into Latin senarii, are from unknown sources. The original Greek form has been preserved only in the case of the first line, as follows, ἔα με κερδαίνοντα κεκλῆσθαι κακόν, which occurs as part of a longer fragment. Vid. A.
